  <h1>DBMS and C Programming Questions & Answers</h1>

  <div class="question">
    <h2>1. What is Database and DBMS?</h2>
    <p>A database is a collection of organized data. DBMS (Database Management System) is software that helps manage databases efficiently.</p>
    <p><strong>Advantages:</strong> Data integrity, security, reduced redundancy, easy access.<br>
    <strong>Disadvantages:</strong> Complex setup, expensive, requires technical knowledge.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="question">
    <h2>2. File Processing vs DBMS</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>File system has data redundancy, DBMS reduces it.</li>
      <li>File system doesn't support multi-user access well, DBMS does.</li>
      <li>File system lacks security, DBMS offers controlled access.</li>
      <li>Data retrieval is slow in file system, fast in DBMS.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="question">
    <h2>11. SQL Commands</h2>
    <pre><code>-- a. Create table
CREATE TABLE students (
  Id INT,
  Name VARCHAR(50),
  Class VARCHAR(20),
  Marks INT
);

-- b. Insert records
INSERT INTO students VALUES (1, 'Anita', '10A', 80);
INSERT INTO students VALUES (2, 'Ram', '10B', 75);

-- c. Display records
SELECT * FROM students;

-- d. Update marks
UPDATE students SET Marks = 85 WHERE Name = 'Anita';

-- e. Delete record
DELETE FROM students WHERE Id = 3;</code></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="question">
    <h2>12. Define Terms</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Data Dictionary:</strong> Metadata storing structure.</li>
      <li><strong>Primary Key:</strong> Unique identifier of a row.</li>
      <li><strong>Relationship:</strong> Link between tables.</li>
      <li><strong>DML:</strong> Data Manipulation Language (SELECT, INSERT).</li>
      <li><strong>SQL:</strong> Structured Query Language for database interaction.</li>
      <li><strong>Data Integrity:</strong> Accuracy and consistency of data.</li>
      <li><strong>DDL:</strong> Data Definition Language (CREATE, ALTER).</li>
      <li><strong>Data Security:</strong> Protecting data from unauthorized access.</li>
      <li><strong>Database System:</strong> System to manage, store, retrieve data.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="question">
    <h2>Unit 2 - C Programming: Functions</h2>
    <p><strong>Define Function:</strong> A block of code to perform a task.</p>
    <p><strong>Syntax:</strong> <code>returnType functionName(parameters)</code></p>
    <p><strong>Types:</strong> Library (e.g., printf) and user-defined functions</p>

    <h3>Components</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Function prototype</li>
      <li>Function call</li>
      <li>Function definition</li>
      <li>Return type</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Function Categories</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><code>int func()</code> - Return type, no argument</li>
      <li><code>int func(int x)</code> - Return type with argument</li>
      <li><code>void func()</code> - No return, no argument</li>
      <li><code>void func(int x)</code> - No return, with argument</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Storage Classes</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Automatic: Default in functions</li>
      <li>External: Global variable</li>
      <li>Register: Stored in CPU register</li>
      <li>Static: Retains value between calls</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Recursive Function Example</h3>
    <pre><code>int factorial(int n) {
  if(n == 1) return 1;
  return n * factorial(n-1);
}</code></pre>

    <h3>Passing Array Example</h3>
    <pre><code>void printArray(int arr[], int size) {
  for(int i = 0; i < size; i++)
    printf("%d ", arr[i]);
}</code></pre>
  </div>
